record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "docs/ci/github-actions.md",
  "line": 33,
  "cap": "AUTH_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "<docs:recommended workflow recipe>",
  "rationale": "The Permissions section recommends `pull_request_target` over `pull_request` so the bot can comment on fork PRs (line 33-34: 'pull_request_target is recommended over pull_request for this reason'). `pull_request_target` runs with the *base* repository's secrets, including a `GITHUB_TOKEN` carrying every permission declared in the workflow (`pull-requests: write` here, often more in real workflows). The accompanying example at line 70-78 uses `actions/checkout@v4` with no `ref:` override — that defaults to the base ref and is safe. The hazard is that the docs (a) do not warn that adding `ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.sha }}` to `actions/checkout` while running under `pull_request_target` checks out attacker-controlled code into a step that holds the privileged base-repo token, and (b) instruct operators to point `nyx-agent.toml` at `path = \".\"` (line 99) so the scanner walks the working tree verbatim. Combined with the `i_own_this = true` template at line 97, a single PR that mutates `nyx-agent.toml` to point `path` at any operator-readable directory turns the agent into a privileged-token-armed file reader against the runner host (and the AI Exploration / NovelFinding workers then carry the contents back into the PR comment via the rendered `path` / `rule` / `cap` fields — see the pass 3 MARKDOWN_INJECTION row). The docs are the trust boundary: this is a documentation-shaped vulnerability where the canonical recipe leads operators into a privilege-escalation pattern. GitHub itself called this class out in 2021 (`Keeping your GitHub Actions and workflows secure: Preventing pwn requests`). Static pass missed because Markdown is not on the input list and the absence of a warning is not a tainted-flow signature.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "n/a — defence is text. Add a boxed warning under the Permissions section: 'When using pull_request_target, do NOT pass `ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.sha }}` to actions/checkout. The base ref's secrets are in scope; checking out fork code lets PR authors plant a nyx-agent.toml override and exfiltrate runner state via the PR comment.' Mirror the GitHub security advisory wording so operators recognise it."
}

notes (pass 5):
- action.yml never echoes the bearer (line 73/88 confine GITHUB_TOKEN to env, never argv); good. The composite uses `bash` with `set -euo pipefail` which propagates non-zero exits — fine.
- ${{ github.event.pull_request.number }} at line 97 is integer-typed by GitHub before injection; not a string-injection sink on its own (verified: GHA serialises numeric event fields as bare integers without quoting metachars). Left out of the OS_COMMAND row above.
- the existing pass-2 `--since-ref` git-option-injection row becomes *operator-reachable but not fork-attacker-reachable* under this action.yml because github.base_ref is repo-controlled. A consumer workflow that swaps in github.head_ref would lift it to fork-reachable; flagged here, not raised as a separate row.
- composite Action workflow has no `permissions:` block of its own; it inherits the caller's. Acceptable for composite Actions, but worth a doc note that the caller must grant exactly `pull-requests: write` (not blanket `write-all`).
